1
00:00:21,527 --> 00:00:25,076
[Soft instrumental music]

2
00:00:38,487 --> 00:00:40,205
[Groans]

3
00:00:46,887 --> 00:00:50,163
<i>KAREN: He even took the gramophone
on safari.</i>

4
00:00:52,807 --> 00:00:56,516
<i>Three rifles, supplies for a month...</i>

5
00:00:57,607 --> 00:00:58,881
<i>and Mozart.</i>

6
00:01:01,287 --> 00:01:03,721
<i>He began our friendship with a gift.</i>

7
00:01:06,367 --> 00:01:09,723
<i>And later, not long before Tsavo...</i>

8
00:01:10,687 --> 00:01:14,600
<i>he gave me another. An incredible gift.</i>

9
00:01:15,487 --> 00:01:18,479
<i>A glimpse of the world through God's eye...</i>

10
00:01:19,767 --> 00:01:21,485
<i>and I thought.</i>

11
00:01:21,847 --> 00:01:24,361
<i>"Yes, I see.</i>

12
00:01:25,487 --> 00:01:27,717
<i>"This is the way it was intended."</i>

13
00:01:32,007 --> 00:01:36,046
<i>I've written about all the others,
not because I loved them less...</i>

14
00:01:36,127 --> 00:01:39,676
<i>but because they were clearer, easier.</i>

15
00:01:41,807 --> 00:01:43,843
<i>He was waiting for me there.</i>

16
00:01:47,327 --> 00:01:50,956
<i>But I've gone ahead of my story.
He'd have hated that.</i>

17
00:01:51,767 --> 00:01:54,327
<i>Denys loved to hear a story told well.</i>

18
00:01:56,367 --> 00:01:57,846
<i>You see...</i>

19
00:01:59,167 --> 00:02:03,445
<i>I had a farm in Africa
at the foot of the Ngong Hills.</i>

20
00:02:04,567 --> 00:02:06,478
<i>But it began before that.</i>

21
00:02:06,967 --> 00:02:09,242
<i>It really began in Denmark.</i>

22
00:02:10,087 --> 00:02:11,918
[Gunshots firing]

23
00:02:16,327 --> 00:02:18,682
<i>KAREN: And there I knew two brothers.</i>

24
00:02:19,127 --> 00:02:22,483
<i>One was my lover, and one was my friend.</i>

25
00:02:22,567 --> 00:02:26,276
- It's too cold for champagne.
- It's too cold for anything but.

26
00:02:31,327 --> 00:02:35,605
- You said you'd be at Klampenborg.
- I thought I'd come, but then I didn't.

27
00:02:37,847 --> 00:02:39,166
Was it fun?

28
00:02:43,447 --> 00:02:44,675
Tanne.

29
00:02:45,767 --> 00:02:47,519
Tanne, come on.

30
00:02:48,287 --> 00:02:50,596
It's not as though you loved him.

31
00:02:50,687 --> 00:02:52,803
You'd like to be a baroness, that's all.

32
00:02:52,967 --> 00:02:54,400
- He lied to me.
- Of course.

33
00:02:54,887 --> 00:02:57,481
Would you be in bed with him otherwise?

34
00:02:57,607 --> 00:03:00,201
My brother's only dull, but not stupid.

35
00:03:04,367 --> 00:03:05,686
Pretend it's Hans.

36
00:03:05,767 --> 00:03:06,836
[Gunshot fires]

37
00:03:09,127 --> 00:03:10,719
BROR: Where would you go?
KAREN: Anywhere.

38
00:03:10,807 --> 00:03:14,561
KAREN: America. Ceylon.
I would even go to Australia.

39
00:03:16,167 --> 00:03:19,682
Perhaps not Australia.
But I've got to be away from here.

40
00:03:19,767 --> 00:03:23,237
I'll give you all I've got.
That should get you into town.

41
00:03:23,967 --> 00:03:25,798
God, it was fun. Money.

42
00:03:27,127 --> 00:03:28,765
You could marry me.

43
00:03:29,007 --> 00:03:32,044
I have to marry a virgin.
I can't stand criticism.

44
00:03:32,327 --> 00:03:34,124
For the money, I mean.

45
00:03:37,007 --> 00:03:38,235
Probably.

46
00:03:38,527 --> 00:03:41,485
Listen to me. I've got no life at all.

47
00:03:41,767 --> 00:03:45,760
They wouldn't teach me anything useful,
and now I've failed to marry.

48
00:03:45,847 --> 00:03:49,362
<i>You know the punishment for that.
"Miss Dinesen's at home."</i>

49
00:03:49,687 --> 00:03:51,757
And you've gone through all your money.

50
00:03:51,847 --> 00:03:55,601
You're off seducing the servant girls.
We're a pair, you and I.

51
00:03:56,367 --> 00:03:59,882
I mean, at least we're friends.
We might be all right...

52
00:03:59,967 --> 00:04:03,323
and if we weren't,
at least we'd have been somewhere.

53
00:04:03,887 --> 00:04:06,606
You don't think you're being too romantic?

54
00:04:14,007 --> 00:04:16,521
BROR: Am I supposed to think
you're serious?

55
00:04:19,847 --> 00:04:22,042
<i>KAREN: I had a farm in Africa.</i>

56
00:04:25,367 --> 00:04:30,043
<i>I had a farm in Africa
at the foot of the Ngong Hills.</i>

57
00:04:43,767 --> 00:04:46,725
[Dramatic instrumental music]

58
00:05:43,847 --> 00:05:46,759
[Sweeping instrumental music]

59
00:07:22,287 --> 00:07:23,481
Good morning.

60
00:07:23,567 --> 00:07:26,525
KAREN: Have you had trouble?
DENYS: Now and then. Have you?

61
00:07:26,887 --> 00:07:30,436
- I'm travelling to Nairobi.
- You caught the right train then.

62
00:07:33,167 --> 00:07:34,998
Get away from there!

63
00:07:35,087 --> 00:07:36,202
Shoo!

64
00:07:37,207 --> 00:07:39,562
That's all my crystal, my Limoges.

65
00:07:39,727 --> 00:07:40,796
[Exclaims knowingly]

66
00:07:40,967 --> 00:07:42,605
They didn't know it was Limoges.

67
00:07:42,687 --> 00:07:44,678
[Denys speaks in African language]

68
00:07:46,327 --> 00:07:47,965
You plan to stay then?

69
00:07:48,047 --> 00:07:51,278
I've come out to marry Baron Blixen.
Do you know him?

70
00:07:51,367 --> 00:07:52,561
Bror? Yes.

71
00:07:52,647 --> 00:07:54,558
We plan to start a dairy.

72
00:07:55,887 --> 00:07:58,765
Are you quite famous?
They stopped the train for you.

73
00:07:58,847 --> 00:08:00,644
DENYS: It's rude not to here.

74
00:08:01,207 --> 00:08:04,563
A dairy? Isn't it a bit soon for that?
Milk at the door?

75
00:08:04,687 --> 00:08:06,564
[Train whistle blowing]

76
00:08:07,567 --> 00:08:09,876
- Aren't you boarding?
- I'm going on.

77
00:08:09,967 --> 00:08:11,366
On? To where?

78
00:08:11,527 --> 00:08:14,644
Mention the ivory to Berkeley Cole.
Bror knows him.

79
00:08:15,407 --> 00:08:18,126
- I'm Baroness Blixen!
- Not yet.

80
00:08:19,487 --> 00:08:21,159
Finch Hatton, Denys!

81
00:08:27,967 --> 00:08:30,561
I am Farah Aden. We can go now.

82
00:08:30,647 --> 00:08:34,356
- Where is Baron Blixen?
- He is at Muthaiga. Please come.

83
00:08:39,367 --> 00:08:42,006
[Farah speaking African language]

84
00:08:44,167 --> 00:08:45,759
KAREN: Where is Muthaiga?

85
00:08:46,327 --> 00:08:49,876
Muthaiga is a club
where British go for drinking. Please.

86
00:08:54,207 --> 00:08:56,437
[Farah speaking African language]

87
00:08:58,167 --> 00:09:02,206
Listen, on the train are my crates
with china and crystal.

88
00:09:02,767 --> 00:09:06,806
- Do you know china?
- Yes. China, it can break.

89
00:09:07,127 --> 00:09:09,880
[Tribal instrumental music]

90
00:09:50,087 --> 00:09:51,122
KAREN: Stay.

91
00:10:04,687 --> 00:10:07,963
Excuse me, I'm looking for Baron Blixen.

92
00:10:08,127 --> 00:10:09,321
Rajiv.

93
00:10:16,487 --> 00:10:20,275
<i>- I wondered if you might tell me...
- Memsahibs must not be here.</i>

94
00:10:21,007 --> 00:10:24,443
<i>- I'm simply looking for someone...
- Memsahibs must not be here.</i>

95
00:10:32,527 --> 00:10:33,562
BROR: Tanne.

96
00:10:33,647 --> 00:10:35,877
BROR: Where have you been?
KAREN: Where have you been?

97
00:10:35,967 --> 00:10:39,437
Arranging things. How was the trip?
You can tell me later.

98
00:10:40,767 --> 00:10:42,166
Would you like to change?

99
00:10:42,247 --> 00:10:45,557
<i>- My luggage is still on the train.
- Room "D." Head of the stairs.</i>

100
00:10:45,647 --> 00:10:47,478
I haven't gotten a ring. Do you care?

101
00:10:47,567 --> 00:10:49,239
KAREN: Did you think I wouldn't come?

102
00:10:49,327 --> 00:10:51,283
I thought you wouldn't want to
spend the money.

103
00:10:51,367 --> 00:10:53,562
BROR: You will love it here.
The servants are great.

104
00:10:53,647 --> 00:10:54,841
BROR: Shall we get a drink?

105
00:10:54,927 --> 00:10:57,043
BROR: We've got almost one hour
before the wedding.

106
00:10:57,127 --> 00:10:58,116
One hour?

107
00:10:58,447 --> 00:11:00,517
[Traditional instrumental
wedding music playing]

108
00:11:08,927 --> 00:11:11,919
- Is this all right?
- I wondered what colour you'd choose.

109
00:11:12,407 --> 00:11:16,559
- It's ivory. God, I've got this man's ivory.
- Whose ivory?

110
00:11:19,167 --> 00:11:21,317
[People cheering excitedly]

111
00:11:35,087 --> 00:11:38,477
I'm Sarah, Lady Belfield.
Shall I stand up for you?

112
00:11:39,007 --> 00:11:40,235
Short or long, Blix?

113
00:11:40,327 --> 00:11:43,125
Long, please. Give me time to adjust to it.

114
00:11:44,567 --> 00:11:46,125
Settle down, all.

115
00:11:46,607 --> 00:11:49,326
By the authority of His Majesty's
Government vested in me...

116
00:11:49,407 --> 00:11:53,878
<i>I declare that the Baron Bror Von Blixen,
citizen of Sweden and...</i>

117
00:11:55,487 --> 00:11:58,718
- What's your name, my dear?
- Damn it, Henry, I told you her name.

118
00:11:58,807 --> 00:12:00,763
Karen Christentze Dinesen.

119
00:12:00,967 --> 00:12:04,562
Karen Christentze Dinesen,
a female subject of the King of Denmark...

120
00:12:04,647 --> 00:12:07,036
are henceforth united man and wife.

121
00:12:07,127 --> 00:12:08,446
[All cheering]

122
00:12:08,527 --> 00:12:11,485
God save this company, God save the King.

123
00:12:11,887 --> 00:12:13,479
ALL: God save the King!

124
00:12:16,807 --> 00:12:18,479
Thank you for this.

125
00:12:19,967 --> 00:12:22,401
<i>DELAMERE: "Did you hear
about Shuttleworth?""No," I said.</i>

126
00:12:22,487 --> 00:12:25,763
<i>"He's living up country," he says,
"in a tree with a baboon."</i>

127
00:12:25,847 --> 00:12:29,635
<i>"Male or female?" I said to him.
"Female, of course," he says.</i>

128
00:12:29,727 --> 00:12:32,560
There's nothing queer
about old Shuttleworth.

129
00:12:32,687 --> 00:12:33,915
[All laughing]

130
00:12:34,087 --> 00:12:35,918
Where's your muddleheaded husband?

131
00:12:36,007 --> 00:12:39,761
The Governor's at the punch bowl,
thank you, hoping to avoid you.

132
00:12:39,847 --> 00:12:43,396
Would you like to meet the bride?
Or did you come just for the whiskey?

133
00:12:43,567 --> 00:12:45,762
Not for the company, God knows.

134
00:12:46,247 --> 00:12:49,125
Lord Delamere,
may I present Baroness Blixen.

135
00:12:49,327 --> 00:12:53,115
Baroness Blixen, Lord Delamere,
such as he is.

136
00:12:54,447 --> 00:12:58,281
- Baroness. A Swede, are you?
- No, Danish, actually.

137
00:12:58,727 --> 00:13:01,116
The little country next to Germany.

138
00:13:01,767 --> 00:13:04,884
If it comes to war,
where will Denmark stand?

139
00:13:06,007 --> 00:13:09,636
On its own, I hope. We do have that history.

140
00:13:10,607 --> 00:13:13,644
Is there something we can call you
that gets round this Baroness?

141
00:13:13,727 --> 00:13:17,436
- What do they call you?
- D, if I'm lucky.

142
00:13:17,687 --> 00:13:19,917
[People cheering excitedly]

143
00:13:28,767 --> 00:13:31,964
My stupid name's Felicity,
but I do like your dress.

144
00:13:32,927 --> 00:13:34,042
Thank you.

145
00:13:34,407 --> 00:13:38,320
- It's not much of a hat.
- It's meant to be stunning.

146
00:13:39,367 --> 00:13:44,043
- We die of sunstroke here.
- At least I'm safe from the mosquitoes.

147
00:13:44,767 --> 00:13:46,166
The big ones.

148
00:13:49,807 --> 00:13:52,765
- You nervous?
- Should I be?

149
00:13:54,007 --> 00:13:57,238
You know, wedding night and all that.

150
00:13:58,927 --> 00:14:01,157
[People cheering excitedly]

151
00:14:12,847 --> 00:14:16,157
So they're both of them naked
and not a shrub in sight.

152
00:14:17,647 --> 00:14:22,118
- Have you met Vicky Gresham?
- Hello, Baroness, I'd curtsy but I'm drunk.

153
00:14:24,047 --> 00:14:26,277
- May I see you, please?
- Excuse me.

154
00:14:28,687 --> 00:14:32,566
If you want any friends, Tanne,
I'd make them here. There is no one else.

155
00:14:32,967 --> 00:14:34,798
I want to see my house.

156
00:14:36,567 --> 00:14:40,242
You may want to change.
It's a two-hour ride.

157
00:14:51,047 --> 00:14:52,036
KAREN: Excuse me.

158
00:15:03,887 --> 00:15:06,640
COLE: My God, these people drink.

159
00:15:07,327 --> 00:15:09,204
<i>I'm sorry, I was just...</i>

160
00:15:10,767 --> 00:15:13,804
- It's all right.
- I'm afraid you've caught me snooping.

161
00:15:13,887 --> 00:15:16,845
It's not my room, it's Denys',
and Denys won't mind.

162
00:15:16,927 --> 00:15:18,918
It's a thing about Denys, he doesn't mind.

163
00:15:19,007 --> 00:15:21,441
Are you Cole?

164
00:15:21,527 --> 00:15:22,562
Berkeley Cole.

165
00:15:22,647 --> 00:15:26,196
- I brought the ivory with me on the train.
- Well, thank you.

166
00:15:29,007 --> 00:15:31,521
- Are you taking your quinine?
- Oh, yes.

167
00:15:32,767 --> 00:15:36,396
He has got lovely books.
Does he lend them?

168
00:15:37,247 --> 00:15:39,203
We had a friend, Hopworth.

169
00:15:40,527 --> 00:15:43,644
He got a book and didn't return it.
Denys was furious.

170
00:15:43,727 --> 00:15:46,799
<i>I said, "Denys, you wouldn't
lose a friend over a book, would you?"</i>

171
00:15:46,887 --> 00:15:48,479
<i>And he said, "No!</i>

172
00:15:49,167 --> 00:15:50,998
<i>"But he has, hasn't he?"</i>

173
00:15:51,527 --> 00:15:52,960
[Laughing]

174
00:15:54,567 --> 00:15:58,242
COLE: Did you come out through London?
KAREN: From Rome actually.

175
00:15:58,447 --> 00:16:00,836
I thought you might have a newspaper.

176
00:16:00,927 --> 00:16:02,997
KAREN: No, sorry.

177
00:16:03,327 --> 00:16:05,158
Nothing in them anyway.

178
00:16:07,007 --> 00:16:10,761
I had a friend who I used to take
to the dances at Oxford.

179
00:16:10,847 --> 00:16:13,077
They were in June by the river.

180
00:16:13,407 --> 00:16:17,161
She always wore a new silk dress.

181
00:16:17,407 --> 00:16:19,796
I think you're wearing her perfume.

182
00:16:28,047 --> 00:16:31,722
No, it's very nice, but it's not the same.

183
00:16:34,127 --> 00:16:35,446
We can go now.

184
00:16:49,607 --> 00:16:52,883
[Natives singing tribal song]

185
00:17:15,567 --> 00:17:18,365
[Bror speaking African language]

186
00:17:19,927 --> 00:17:21,679
[All speak African language]

187
00:17:31,767 --> 00:17:34,565
This is Belknap. He runs the farm.

188
00:17:35,447 --> 00:17:37,085
Good evening, ma'am.

189
00:17:43,007 --> 00:17:45,601
This is your cook. Name is Esa.

190
00:17:46,487 --> 00:17:47,602
Esa.

191
00:17:52,287 --> 00:17:54,755
And this is Juma. Houseboy.

192
00:17:56,647 --> 00:17:57,841
Juma.

193
00:17:58,847 --> 00:18:00,519
[Speaking African language]

194
00:18:01,127 --> 00:18:03,197
Come, see your house.

195
00:18:04,447 --> 00:18:07,519
KAREN: When you leave me,
I'm going to marry Berkeley Cole.

196
00:18:07,607 --> 00:18:09,040
BROR: A man in trade.

197
00:18:09,367 --> 00:18:10,925
Is that what he does?

198
00:18:11,007 --> 00:18:14,397
He is thick with the Somalis.
There's a crowd of them up on his land...

199
00:18:14,487 --> 00:18:18,446
who think he's some sort of prince.
He sells Finch Hatton's ivory.

200
00:18:19,287 --> 00:18:21,642
Belknap is a cheery sort.

201
00:18:21,847 --> 00:18:25,317
Had a place of his own.
Went belly up trying to grow flax.

202
00:18:27,087 --> 00:18:28,759
KAREN: Does he know cattle?

203
00:18:29,087 --> 00:18:33,285
I didn't buy cattle.
We're going to grow coffee instead.

204
00:18:41,047 --> 00:18:43,038
That's not what we planned.

205
00:18:43,447 --> 00:18:45,961
BROR: You were in Denmark, I had to decide.

206
00:18:46,207 --> 00:18:48,084
We made a decision.

207
00:18:49,127 --> 00:18:52,278
KAREN: We don't know a thing about coffee.
BROR: You plant it, it grows.

208
00:18:52,367 --> 00:18:54,517
My mother put her money up to do a dairy.

209
00:18:54,607 --> 00:18:58,441
She doesn't care whether
it's cows or coffee as long as it pays.

210
00:18:58,527 --> 00:19:00,438
You must be with a herd
or things go wrong.

211
00:19:00,527 --> 00:19:03,485
I didn't come to Africa to sit with silly cows.

212
00:19:03,567 --> 00:19:05,956
Just tell her we changed our minds.

213
00:19:06,367 --> 00:19:10,519
Next time you change your mind,
you do it with your money.

214
00:19:12,647 --> 00:19:15,639
They bought you a title. They didn't buy me.

215
00:19:17,007 --> 00:19:18,156
Juma.

216
00:19:18,967 --> 00:19:22,164
Fetch some wine for my lover's brother.

217
00:19:27,527 --> 00:19:29,245
I think you're tired.

218
00:19:35,807 --> 00:19:37,126
[Whispering] Be careful.

219
00:19:42,647 --> 00:19:45,286
Did I tell you Hans came to say goodbye?

220
00:19:57,687 --> 00:20:00,201
[Farah instructing in African language]

221
00:20:03,927 --> 00:20:07,044
KAREN: Where is Baron Blixen?
FARAH: He's gone to hunt.

222
00:20:08,127 --> 00:20:12,325
- Did he say when he would be back?
- He says he can come before the rain.

223
00:20:13,967 --> 00:20:15,923
Is it going to rain today?

224
00:20:17,167 --> 00:20:19,635
It can be many days before the rains.

225
00:20:47,887 --> 00:20:49,798
[Baboons screeching]

226
00:20:51,047 --> 00:20:53,845
BELKNAP: In Ohio we put up scarecrows
to keep the birds away.

227
00:20:53,927 --> 00:20:56,839
Here you hope there're enough leopards
to keep down the baboons.

228
00:20:56,927 --> 00:20:59,202
'Course they'll take your dog, too.
That's Africa.

229
00:20:59,287 --> 00:21:02,245
KAREN: How much will we plant?
BELKNAP: 1,000 acres, the Baron says.

230
00:21:02,327 --> 00:21:03,919
How long will that take?

231
00:21:04,007 --> 00:21:07,522
That depends on Kinanjui.
He's the chief of the Kikuyu.

232
00:21:07,607 --> 00:21:11,805
BELKNAP: Got a deal with him to get help.
KAREN: When will be our first harvest?

233
00:21:12,127 --> 00:21:15,802
These are seedlings.
It'll be three, maybe four years.

234
00:21:16,687 --> 00:21:17,915
Four years!

235
00:21:18,087 --> 00:21:21,557
If they bear at all.
No one's ever tried coffee this high.

236
00:21:22,447 --> 00:21:25,564
And what are we going to live on
for four years?

237
00:21:25,647 --> 00:21:29,117
I'm working to get home.
Now, if you haven't got it...

238
00:21:29,207 --> 00:21:32,040
it'd be good if you could tell me right now.

239
00:21:33,407 --> 00:21:35,204
We will plant 500.

240
00:21:37,767 --> 00:21:41,680
Chief Kinanjui, I have heard
that you are a wise chief...

241
00:21:41,767 --> 00:21:45,726
Not now, please.
And I look forward to our dealings.

242
00:21:46,847 --> 00:21:48,963
Your Kikuyu are good workers.

243
00:21:49,127 --> 00:21:53,678
I look forward to dealing
with them honestly, and fairly.

244
00:21:53,887 --> 00:21:56,640
This chief has no British.

245
00:21:59,767 --> 00:22:03,362
- Tell him that I am Baroness Blixen.
- This chief knows that.

246
00:22:06,327 --> 00:22:08,079
Tell him what I said.

247
00:22:08,287 --> 00:22:10,596
[Farah translating in African language]

248
00:22:18,287 --> 00:22:20,596
[Speaking African language]

249
00:22:40,047 --> 00:22:43,960
- What did he say?
- He says these Kikuyu can do this work.

250
00:22:48,247 --> 00:22:50,124
<i>KAREN: Farah, what else did he...</i>

251
00:23:10,807 --> 00:23:12,604
Your leg is very sick.

252
00:23:15,407 --> 00:23:18,046
You must come to the house for medicine.

253
00:23:19,887 --> 00:23:21,923
- Does he understand me?
- Yes.

254
00:23:26,167 --> 00:23:29,603
If you don't come,
the other boys will say you are afraid.

255
00:23:33,767 --> 00:23:36,327
I myself will think only that you are foolish.

256
00:23:37,367 --> 00:23:41,519
This boy must come to my house
for treatment. See that he does.

257
00:23:44,687 --> 00:23:46,678
What else did Kinanjui say?

258
00:23:47,447 --> 00:23:50,041
He says coffee must not grow this high.

259
00:23:51,367 --> 00:23:54,200
Never mind. He's a chief, but he's a Kikuyu.

260
00:24:11,407 --> 00:24:14,126
[Clock cuckooing]

261
00:24:16,567 --> 00:24:19,081
[Natives singing tribal song]

262
00:24:26,567 --> 00:24:31,118
If you put a dam here to stop the water
then I can make a pond here.

263
00:24:31,207 --> 00:24:32,799
Do you know how to make a pond?

264
00:24:32,887 --> 00:24:37,199
- This water must go home to Mombasa.
- It can go home after we make a pond.

265
00:24:38,247 --> 00:24:40,283
This water lives at Mombasa.

266
00:24:40,367 --> 00:24:41,880
[Bell ringing]

267
00:24:45,807 --> 00:24:47,126
KAREN: Come, then.

268
00:24:48,407 --> 00:24:50,796
[Melancholic instrumental music]

269
00:25:32,007 --> 00:25:33,963
[Horse neighing softly]

270
00:25:37,727 --> 00:25:40,400
[Horse neighing loudly]

271
00:25:42,727 --> 00:25:44,080
[Exclaiming in annoyance]

272
00:25:44,167 --> 00:25:45,725
[Growling]

273
00:25:53,927 --> 00:25:55,360
DENYS: I wouldn't run.

274
00:25:57,087 --> 00:26:00,284
DENYS: If you do,
she'll think you're something good to eat.

275
00:26:00,367 --> 00:26:01,595
[Growling menacingly]

276
00:26:03,087 --> 00:26:06,557
- Do you have a gun?
- She won't like the smell of you.

277
00:26:07,367 --> 00:26:10,120
KAREN: Shoot it.
DENYS: She's had breakfast.

278
00:26:12,007 --> 00:26:14,362
[Exclaiming fearfully]

279
00:26:15,287 --> 00:26:16,845
Please shoot her.

280
00:26:17,527 --> 00:26:19,404
Let's give her a moment.

281
00:26:20,447 --> 00:26:22,244
Oh, my God, shoot her!

282
00:26:31,847 --> 00:26:35,123
Just how much closer
did you expect to let her come?

283
00:26:35,367 --> 00:26:39,440
A bit. She wanted to see if you'd run.
That's how they decide.

284
00:26:39,527 --> 00:26:42,166
DENYS: A lot like people.
KAREN: She almost had me for lunch.

285
00:26:42,247 --> 00:26:45,398
- It wasn't her fault. She's a lion.
- It wasn't mine.

286
00:26:45,487 --> 00:26:48,047
Doesn't that outfit come with a rifle?

287
00:26:48,247 --> 00:26:50,203
It's on my saddle.

288
00:26:50,367 --> 00:26:53,325
Better keep it with you.
Your horse isn't much of a shot.

289
00:26:54,087 --> 00:26:56,237
For Berkeley. He's brought you presents.

290
00:26:57,007 --> 00:26:58,998
DENYS: We stopped by your house,
then came looking.

291
00:26:59,087 --> 00:27:01,157
Good Lord, you are sweet.

292
00:27:02,007 --> 00:27:05,238
You're on the road actually.
We're off to Magadi to shoot some ivory.

293
00:27:05,327 --> 00:27:08,239
At least I have something good to offer you.

294
00:27:09,247 --> 00:27:12,319
Did you intend to tell Berkeley
what a fool I was?

295
00:27:12,567 --> 00:27:14,478
She had a lion a bit interested.

296
00:27:14,567 --> 00:27:17,843
A bit? A bit, but not enough to bite.

297
00:27:18,127 --> 00:27:22,040
It's all right to take a chance
as long as you're the only one who'll pay.

298
00:27:22,127 --> 00:27:23,242
Wouldn't you say so?

299
00:27:23,327 --> 00:27:25,682
I'd say that it sounds
more like something you'd say.

300
00:27:25,767 --> 00:27:27,041
- Thank you.
- Not at all.

301
00:27:27,127 --> 00:27:28,924
- Where's Blix?
- Hunting.

302
00:27:29,207 --> 00:27:31,516
- Has he been out long?
- Yes.

303
00:27:33,487 --> 00:27:36,126
You'll need a good chat then.
Shall we stay for supper?

304
00:27:36,207 --> 00:27:37,925
Blix will have jackets we can use.

305
00:27:38,007 --> 00:27:41,761
- Do I have anything to say in this?
- Not really, but we'll hear you out.

306
00:27:42,007 --> 00:27:44,475
- Then I would like you to stay.
- Good.

307
00:27:45,607 --> 00:27:46,801
Denys.

308
00:27:47,047 --> 00:27:48,958
I don't know. Do you sing?

309
00:27:51,287 --> 00:27:52,561
Never.

310
00:27:52,647 --> 00:27:56,686
- Can you tell a story then?
- I happen to be very good at stories.

311
00:27:58,527 --> 00:27:59,755
I believe that.

312
00:28:00,287 --> 00:28:02,562
[Pleasant instrumental music]

313
00:28:02,967 --> 00:28:05,083
DENYS: What's happened to the cows?
For the dairy?

314
00:28:05,167 --> 00:28:08,523
KAREN: We changed our minds.
We'll grow coffee instead.

315
00:28:08,607 --> 00:28:11,326
DENYS: A bit risky, this high.
KAREN: So I've been told.

316
00:28:11,487 --> 00:28:15,036
DENYS: Didn't seem to bother you.
KAREN: I think they just haven't tried.

317
00:28:15,127 --> 00:28:18,199
KAREN: Every time I turn my back,
it wants to go wild again.

318
00:28:18,527 --> 00:28:20,040
It will go wild.

319
00:28:25,007 --> 00:28:26,918
- Your man...
- Kanuthia.

320
00:28:27,887 --> 00:28:29,923
- He's not Kikuyu?
- No.

321
00:28:32,287 --> 00:28:34,005
Shall I see that he's given supper?

322
00:28:34,087 --> 00:28:36,601
Don't do anything for him,
thank you, Baroness.

323
00:28:38,127 --> 00:28:41,085
COLE: It's true of Somalis.
The only tribe that knows horses.

324
00:28:41,167 --> 00:28:45,001
And they don't drink, charge interest,
or chase other men's wives.

325
00:28:47,927 --> 00:28:49,406
<i>Got to go to town for that.</i>

326
00:28:53,207 --> 00:28:57,962
Did you know that in all of literature
there is no poem celebrating the foot?

327
00:28:58,487 --> 00:29:03,003
There's lips, there's eyes, hands,
face, hair, breasts...

328
00:29:03,247 --> 00:29:07,399
legs, arms, even the knees,
but not one verse for the poor old foot.

329
00:29:09,887 --> 00:29:11,400
Why do you think that is?

330
00:29:11,727 --> 00:29:15,083
Priorities, I suppose.
Did you think you would make one?

331
00:29:15,647 --> 00:29:17,842
The problem is,
there's nothing to rhyme it with.

332
00:29:17,927 --> 00:29:19,121
- Put.
- It's not a noun.

333
00:29:19,207 --> 00:29:20,276
Doesn't matter.

334
00:29:20,367 --> 00:29:24,326
<i>"Along he came and he did put
upon my farm his clumsy foot"</i>

335
00:29:24,527 --> 00:29:26,085
[Chuckling]

336
00:29:30,207 --> 00:29:32,198
We should have a story now.

337
00:29:36,607 --> 00:29:39,440
When I tell a story to my nieces at home...

338
00:29:39,607 --> 00:29:42,405
one of them always provides
the first sentence.

339
00:29:44,407 --> 00:29:46,637
- Anything?
- Absolutely anything.

340
00:29:50,367 --> 00:29:54,838
There was a wandering Chinese
named Cheng Huan...

341
00:29:57,567 --> 00:29:59,637
living in Limehouse...

342
00:30:00,047 --> 00:30:03,119
and a girl named Shirley.

343
00:30:05,687 --> 00:30:08,155
Who spoke perfect Chinese...

344
00:30:08,527 --> 00:30:11,360
which she learned
from her missionary parents.

345
00:30:12,367 --> 00:30:15,962
Cheng Huan lived alone
in a room on Formosa Street...

346
00:30:16,727 --> 00:30:18,683
above the Blue Lantern.

347
00:30:18,847 --> 00:30:20,917
[Soft instrumental music]

348
00:30:21,047 --> 00:30:22,878
He sat at his window...

349
00:30:25,047 --> 00:30:27,880
and in his poor listening heart...

350
00:30:28,767 --> 00:30:31,839
<i>strange echoes of his home and country...</i>

351
00:30:39,927 --> 00:30:43,397
[Soft instrumental music continues]

352
00:30:59,407 --> 00:31:01,716
KAREN: They found them there
the next morning...

353
00:31:01,807 --> 00:31:03,877
in their room above the Blue Lantern.

354
00:31:04,367 --> 00:31:06,676
<i>The dead child and the warlord...</i>

355
00:31:07,567 --> 00:31:11,401
with Cheng Huan's love gift
coiled about his neck.

356
00:31:17,567 --> 00:31:19,683
Had you been to those places?

357
00:31:20,007 --> 00:31:23,204
I have been a mental traveller.

358
00:31:24,087 --> 00:31:25,645
COLE: Till now.
KAREN: Yes.

359
00:31:25,807 --> 00:31:28,844
Wasn't this England? Excuse me, Denmark?

360
00:31:30,207 --> 00:31:31,765
I like my things.

361
00:31:32,567 --> 00:31:35,400
And when you travelled before,
in your mind...

362
00:31:35,847 --> 00:31:37,963
did you carry so much luggage?

363
00:31:38,367 --> 00:31:41,404
A mental traveller
hasn't the need to eat or sleep...

364
00:31:41,967 --> 00:31:43,764
or entertain.

365
00:31:47,087 --> 00:31:48,361
You're right.

366
00:31:49,047 --> 00:31:52,244
Anyway, aren't you pleased
that I brought my crystal and my china?

367
00:31:52,927 --> 00:31:54,485
And your stories, yes.

368
00:31:54,807 --> 00:31:58,766
<i>COLE AND DENYS: [Singing]
The conquering heroes come</i>

369
00:31:59,647 --> 00:32:04,562
<i>Sound the trumpets
Beat the drums</i>

370
00:32:05,647 --> 00:32:07,797
[Cole and Denys humming]

371
00:32:14,527 --> 00:32:18,281
KAREN: But I want you to come often.
COLE: I'd like that very much.

372
00:32:18,487 --> 00:32:21,399
- And you must promise me it will be soon.
- I promise.

373
00:32:23,047 --> 00:32:24,275
Bye.

374
00:32:30,567 --> 00:32:32,319
KAREN: Did you save my life?

375
00:32:33,207 --> 00:32:37,439
No, the lioness did that. She walked away.

376
00:32:38,047 --> 00:32:40,003
So I am not indebted then?

377
00:32:41,367 --> 00:32:42,561
But I am.

378
00:32:43,767 --> 00:32:45,883
We pay our storytellers here.

379
00:32:50,007 --> 00:32:51,326
It's lovely.

380
00:32:53,167 --> 00:32:57,604
But my stories are free
and your present's much too dear.

381
00:32:59,487 --> 00:33:01,398
Write them down sometime.

382
00:33:08,167 --> 00:33:10,044
Take care, Finch Hatton.

383
00:33:11,127 --> 00:33:13,482
You wouldn't rather call me Denys?

384
00:33:18,607 --> 00:33:19,835
Baroness.

385
00:33:29,047 --> 00:33:30,924
[Thunder rumbling in the distance]

386
00:33:31,927 --> 00:33:34,316
[Pleasant instrumental music]

387
00:33:54,687 --> 00:33:56,359
What are you doing?

388
00:33:58,567 --> 00:34:00,478
I want you to come home.

389
00:34:05,567 --> 00:34:07,285
[Thunder rumbling]

390
00:34:16,727 --> 00:34:17,876
Bror.

391
00:34:20,367 --> 00:34:22,517
We never spoke about children.

392
00:34:25,967 --> 00:34:27,286
<i>Did you...</i>

393
00:34:29,487 --> 00:34:30,636
Do you?

394
00:34:31,047 --> 00:34:32,116
Yes.

395
00:34:33,327 --> 00:34:34,919
Is that all right?

396
00:34:53,327 --> 00:34:55,636
These Kikuyu want to be sick now.

397
00:34:56,367 --> 00:34:57,766
Good Lord!

398
00:35:00,287 --> 00:35:02,084
Your leg has got worse.

399
00:35:03,567 --> 00:35:05,523
You should go to hospital.

400
00:35:05,847 --> 00:35:10,238
This leg may be foolish.
It may think not to go to hospital.

401
00:35:12,687 --> 00:35:14,882
This leg will do as it pleases.

402
00:35:16,087 --> 00:35:20,080
But if you will take it to hospital,
I will think that you are wise.

403
00:35:20,487 --> 00:35:24,275
And such a wise man as this,
I would want to work in my house...

404
00:35:24,847 --> 00:35:26,246
for wages.

405
00:35:26,647 --> 00:35:29,878
How much wages would come to
such a wise man as that?

406
00:35:32,847 --> 00:35:35,441
More wages than come from tending goats.

407
00:35:37,367 --> 00:35:39,278
I will speak to this leg.

408
00:35:41,207 --> 00:35:43,641
[Majestic instrumental music]

409
00:35:44,127 --> 00:35:45,845
[Car horn honking]

410
00:36:19,487 --> 00:36:23,366
MAN 1: What about air raids?
DELAMERE: Quiet! One question at a time.

411
00:36:23,447 --> 00:36:25,756
MAN 2: The war's in Europe.
Will it ever reach here?

412
00:36:25,847 --> 00:36:29,965
German East is only 200 miles south.
General Von Lettow is there.

413
00:36:30,047 --> 00:36:31,924
Let's not wait till he joins us at the bar.

414
00:36:32,007 --> 00:36:33,281
BROR: Would we engage them?

415
00:36:33,367 --> 00:36:36,564
This is our war.
You don't have to be involved, but thanks.

416
00:36:36,647 --> 00:36:40,162
I've got crops coming in.
How long is this thing gonna last?

417
00:36:40,607 --> 00:36:42,996
DELAMERE: We just have to stay
and go as we must.

418
00:36:43,087 --> 00:36:45,476
MAN 3: They won't fight if we won't fight.

419
00:36:45,767 --> 00:36:48,361
We could always arm the Masai
and point them south.

420
00:36:48,447 --> 00:36:51,883
Do you want the job of collecting rifles
from the Masai when this is over?

421
00:36:51,967 --> 00:36:54,959
And our women and children?
Shall we bring them into town?

422
00:36:55,047 --> 00:36:57,766
We will deal with that problem as it arises.

423
00:36:57,847 --> 00:36:59,280
Will they use native troops?

424
00:36:59,367 --> 00:37:01,961
I'd assume so, but not Masai!

425
00:37:02,447 --> 00:37:04,358
Berkeley, what about your Somalis?

426
00:37:05,487 --> 00:37:08,877
They'd make very good scouts.
We can cover the area here to the border.

427
00:37:08,967 --> 00:37:11,435
We can gather information
for when the regulars arrive.

428
00:37:11,527 --> 00:37:13,961
DENYS: What's it about? Have you any idea?

429
00:37:14,087 --> 00:37:15,486
[Cole chuckling awkwardly]

430
00:37:15,567 --> 00:37:18,604
COLE: Not really.
DENYS: Then why do you want to get into it?

431
00:37:18,687 --> 00:37:20,279
It's got nothing to do with us.

432
00:37:20,367 --> 00:37:22,801
They've made agreements
we know nothing about.

433
00:37:22,887 --> 00:37:26,163
Victoria and the Kaiser were relatives,
for God's sake.

434
00:37:27,607 --> 00:37:31,566
They divided Africa between them.
Do you know why there's a border?

435
00:37:31,647 --> 00:37:33,717
'Cause she had two mountains
and he had none.

436
00:37:33,807 --> 00:37:35,843
So she gave him Kilimanjaro.

437
00:37:36,327 --> 00:37:39,478
It's a silly argument
between two spoiled countries.

438
00:37:39,567 --> 00:37:44,402
The sooner we do this, the sooner it ends,
the sooner we pick up where we left off.

439
00:37:46,047 --> 00:37:47,366
It may end.

440
00:37:49,207 --> 00:37:51,402
But we're not gonna
pick up where we left off.

441
00:37:51,487 --> 00:37:55,002
You don't have to go! You want to go!

442
00:37:55,447 --> 00:37:57,119
We've got to live here.

443
00:37:57,207 --> 00:38:00,722
- They don't want you.
- They don't know where we stand.

444
00:38:00,807 --> 00:38:04,243
I'm not so fond of their empire
I'd have you shot for it.

445
00:38:04,327 --> 00:38:06,557
More likely chewed on than shot.

446
00:38:06,927 --> 00:38:10,078
The farm will take care of itself,
and you've got Belknap.

447
00:38:10,167 --> 00:38:12,522
The farm will not take care of itself.

448
00:38:12,607 --> 00:38:14,325
That's not the point.

449
00:38:18,487 --> 00:38:20,876
I didn't expect to like you so much.

450
00:38:25,767 --> 00:38:28,759
You're not going to go falling in love,
are you?

451
00:38:30,287 --> 00:38:32,801
Not with someone who's always leaving.

452
00:38:36,047 --> 00:38:39,596
If you need me,
send a runner to find Delamere.

453
00:38:40,047 --> 00:38:41,924
That's where I'll be.

454
00:38:47,847 --> 00:38:51,044
- That's a fine kiss goodbye.
- I'm better at hello.

455
00:38:54,407 --> 00:38:56,875
[Solemn instrumental music]

456
00:39:06,887 --> 00:39:09,401
<i>KAREN: It's an odd feeling, farewell.</i>

457
00:39:10,767 --> 00:39:12,678
<i>There is some envy in it.</i>

458
00:39:14,087 --> 00:39:17,841
<i>Men go off to be tested for courage.</i>

459
00:39:18,167 --> 00:39:21,762
<i>But if we're tested at all it's for patience...</i>

460
00:39:21,927 --> 00:39:23,645
<i>for doing without...</i>

461
00:39:24,487 --> 00:39:27,877
<i>perhaps for how well
we can endure loneliness.</i>

462
00:39:28,887 --> 00:39:30,923
<i>But I had always known that.</i>

463
00:39:31,567 --> 00:39:33,523
[Greeting in African language]

464
00:39:33,647 --> 00:39:35,524
<i>KAREN: It didn't require a war.</i>

465
00:39:36,607 --> 00:39:38,882
<i>I said goodbye to Bror.</i>

466
00:39:39,487 --> 00:39:44,003
<i>Denys left without a word,
which was quite proper.</i>

467
00:39:47,127 --> 00:39:48,640
FELICITY: Hello, the house!

468
00:39:48,887 --> 00:39:50,366
[Dog barking]

469
00:39:50,847 --> 00:39:52,485
KAREN: Felicity.

470
00:39:52,887 --> 00:39:55,276
I thought you might want some meat.

471
00:39:56,287 --> 00:39:57,879
KAREN: Is there any word?

472
00:39:57,967 --> 00:40:02,199
Nothing new. There's not much fighting.
Awful fever, though.

473
00:40:03,927 --> 00:40:06,441
I've got time for tea, I should think.

474
00:40:13,447 --> 00:40:15,358
Are you for the Germans?

475
00:40:18,447 --> 00:40:20,802
Did they send you out to ask me this?

476
00:40:20,887 --> 00:40:24,436
- We had a row about it in town.
- Because of my bad English.

477
00:40:26,047 --> 00:40:28,083
And whose side were you on?

478
00:40:28,727 --> 00:40:29,842
Yours.

479
00:40:35,087 --> 00:40:38,682
They want to send me home to school.
Mother says I'm growing up wild.

480
00:40:38,767 --> 00:40:40,883
- I wanted to ask you about it.
- Me?

481
00:40:42,407 --> 00:40:44,523
You've been around and about.

482
00:40:45,447 --> 00:40:48,678
Some day, I'd like to run
my own show the way you do.

483
00:40:50,487 --> 00:40:53,684
KAREN: Is that what I do?
FELICITY: You don't seem to need us much.

484
00:40:57,047 --> 00:40:58,958
May I ask you something?

485
00:41:01,047 --> 00:41:03,845
I don't know much about men.

486
00:41:07,127 --> 00:41:09,516
I want them to like me, but I...

487
00:41:10,647 --> 00:41:12,922
I want to be let alone, too.

488
00:41:17,007 --> 00:41:19,805
I'm supposed to want to be taken, aren't I?

489
00:41:22,447 --> 00:41:24,165
I've got this book...

490
00:41:26,687 --> 00:41:29,360
but how do you know
when to do what they want you to...

491
00:41:29,447 --> 00:41:32,007
and when not to?

492
00:41:36,927 --> 00:41:39,395
I suppose you ought to call me Karen.

493
00:41:41,247 --> 00:41:42,885
[Clock ticking]

494
00:41:43,407 --> 00:41:45,716
[Soft instrumental music]

495
00:41:50,607 --> 00:41:52,723
[Clock cuckooing]

496
00:41:54,767 --> 00:41:58,077
They need paraffin and tinned food.
Enough for 300 men.

497
00:41:58,167 --> 00:42:00,635
He wants you to send
a white man with the wagon.

498
00:42:00,727 --> 00:42:02,160
Is he all right?

499
00:42:02,247 --> 00:42:04,841
I assume. Well enough to send a message.

500
00:42:05,207 --> 00:42:07,801
And where would my husband
like this wagon sent?

501
00:42:07,887 --> 00:42:10,321
He's with Delamere
on the border near Lake Natron.

502
00:42:10,407 --> 00:42:13,877
- That's confidential, of course.
- I would bear that in mind.

503
00:42:13,967 --> 00:42:15,639
CAPTAIN: Sorry, I only meant...

504
00:42:15,727 --> 00:42:18,287
it wouldn't do
for it to be talk around Nairobi.

505
00:42:18,367 --> 00:42:21,404
CAPTAIN: We have to move you into town.
We can't protect you here.

506
00:42:22,847 --> 00:42:24,519
What do you mean, into town?

507
00:42:24,607 --> 00:42:26,837
With the men gone,
we're worried about the natives.

508
00:42:26,927 --> 00:42:29,282
We have orders.
Women and children into town.

509
00:42:29,487 --> 00:42:32,763
- That is internment, Lieutenant.
- Women and children.

510
00:42:34,647 --> 00:42:36,717
Is that one category or two?

511
00:42:36,927 --> 00:42:38,997
You'll want time to gather your things.

512
00:42:39,087 --> 00:42:41,237
CAPTAIN: I'll send an escort here
for you Thursday.

513
00:42:41,327 --> 00:42:42,999
And I am a captain.

514
00:42:48,167 --> 00:42:49,964
I'm not paid to fight.

515
00:42:51,927 --> 00:42:53,155
No.

516
00:42:55,807 --> 00:42:57,525
Where is Lake Natron?

517
00:42:58,047 --> 00:43:01,801
That's south. Bush country.
It's no place for a white man.

518
00:43:04,527 --> 00:43:06,518
[Natives marshalling oxen]

519
00:43:06,607 --> 00:43:08,677
[Tense instrumental music]

520
00:43:25,407 --> 00:43:28,444
[Pleasant instrumental music]

521
00:43:41,487 --> 00:43:44,047
[Native singing tribal song]

522
00:43:51,407 --> 00:43:53,967
[Sweeping instrumental music]

523
00:44:16,527 --> 00:44:19,087
[Tense instrumental music]

524
00:44:27,927 --> 00:44:29,918
[Oxen mooing]

525
00:44:50,647 --> 00:44:53,241
[Natives singing tribal song]

526
00:45:16,967 --> 00:45:20,004
[Distant roaring]

527
00:45:39,087 --> 00:45:41,806
We should have crossed
the Sand River today.

528
00:45:42,687 --> 00:45:44,518
I may have got us lost.

529
00:45:45,167 --> 00:45:46,566
God is great.

530
00:46:05,047 --> 00:46:06,685
[Birds chirping]

531
00:46:12,767 --> 00:46:14,962
[Natives yelling]

532
00:46:38,847 --> 00:46:42,442
- What the devil are you doing here?
- I'm on my way to Delamere.

533
00:46:42,527 --> 00:46:45,644
COLE: Absurd. We don't send women to war.
KAREN: Well, I'm going.

534
00:46:45,727 --> 00:46:48,560
We haven't time for this.
You don't know where you are.

535
00:46:48,647 --> 00:46:51,366
KAREN: I do now.
COLE: And you'll just get lost again.

536
00:46:52,087 --> 00:46:53,486
I'm going on.

537
00:46:54,167 --> 00:46:56,522
- Talk to her, will you?
- No.

538
00:46:58,367 --> 00:47:00,358
She could be hurt or worse.

539
00:47:00,447 --> 00:47:02,358
I imagine she knows that.

540
00:47:03,127 --> 00:47:04,606
Right, I tried.

541
00:47:10,447 --> 00:47:11,675
DENYS: Here.

542
00:47:13,487 --> 00:47:16,877
Find a spot on the horizon
each morning and steer by it.

543
00:47:17,087 --> 00:47:18,600
<i>South-southwest.</i>

544
00:47:19,127 --> 00:47:20,685
About three days.

545
00:47:21,287 --> 00:47:22,276
I see.

546
00:47:23,247 --> 00:47:26,125
And don't worry about us, we'll be all right.

547
00:47:28,167 --> 00:47:31,398
[Native marshalling oxen]

548
00:47:43,367 --> 00:47:46,279
[Tense instrumental music]

549
00:47:54,767 --> 00:47:56,120
[Sighing]

550
00:48:01,767 --> 00:48:02,916
Farah.

551
00:48:16,247 --> 00:48:18,124
- What is it?
- Masai.

552
00:48:29,527 --> 00:48:32,360
[Tense instrumental music continues]

553
00:49:52,727 --> 00:49:54,365
[Lion growling]

554
00:49:58,327 --> 00:50:00,124
[Natives shouting]

555
00:50:00,287 --> 00:50:03,484
KAREN: Ismail, my rifle, where's my rifle?

556
00:50:03,807 --> 00:50:04,796
Ismail!

557
00:50:05,047 --> 00:50:07,117
[Lion roaring]

558
00:50:07,807 --> 00:50:10,002
[Natives shouting]

559
00:50:23,447 --> 00:50:25,915
[Karen exclaiming in pain]

560
00:50:30,327 --> 00:50:31,555
Get away!

561
00:50:31,807 --> 00:50:33,081
[Lion growling]

562
00:50:33,167 --> 00:50:34,282
Get away!

563
00:50:34,367 --> 00:50:35,720
[Oxen mooing in pain]

564
00:50:41,767 --> 00:50:43,803
[Lion growling]

565
00:50:58,727 --> 00:51:01,195
[Lions continue roaring]

566
00:51:09,207 --> 00:51:12,040
[Oxen mooing in pain]

567
00:51:17,247 --> 00:51:19,966
[Mournful instrumental music]

568
00:51:24,887 --> 00:51:26,843
[Karen exclaiming mournfully]

569
00:51:30,287 --> 00:51:33,643
<i>FARAH: Msabu's bleeding.
She does not have this ox.</i>

570
00:51:35,487 --> 00:51:37,398
This lion is hungry.

571
00:51:38,247 --> 00:51:40,397
He does not have this ox.

572
00:51:41,967 --> 00:51:45,926
This wagon is heavy. It doesn't have this ox.

573
00:51:47,687 --> 00:51:51,236
God is happy. He plays with us.

574
00:52:02,207 --> 00:52:04,118
Tell Blix his wife's here.

575
00:52:21,607 --> 00:52:24,121
[Native marshalling oxen]

576
00:52:46,447 --> 00:52:47,516
Hello, Karen.

577
00:52:48,527 --> 00:52:51,087
Hello, D. Hello, Bror.

578
00:52:51,887 --> 00:52:54,003
I've brought you some things.

579
00:52:55,767 --> 00:52:57,678
You've changed your hair.

580
00:52:57,767 --> 00:52:59,564
[Laughing]

581
00:52:59,727 --> 00:53:02,480
KAREN: You needed supplies...
BROR: Send someone, I said.

582
00:53:02,567 --> 00:53:05,923
You were lucky to get through.
It was really foolish.

583
00:53:06,007 --> 00:53:07,804
KAREN: But I did get through.

584
00:53:09,167 --> 00:53:10,646
And it was fun.

585
00:53:15,927 --> 00:53:17,838
When are you coming home?

586
00:53:20,927 --> 00:53:22,360
Not just yet.

587
00:53:24,367 --> 00:53:27,677
You're not going to help at all
with the farm, are you?

588
00:53:29,727 --> 00:53:30,955
No.

589
00:53:31,527 --> 00:53:34,883
KAREN: I could force you.
I could cut you off.

590
00:53:36,247 --> 00:53:38,397
I'll just hunt professionally.

591
00:53:40,207 --> 00:53:41,925
BROR: I might do it anyway.

592
00:53:46,167 --> 00:53:48,840
It's not the way we thought it would be...

593
00:53:50,887 --> 00:53:52,081
is it?

594
00:53:59,727 --> 00:54:02,400
But I like it that you're honest with me.

595
00:54:03,447 --> 00:54:05,005
I like you, too.

596
00:54:07,647 --> 00:54:09,000
[Whispering] Tanne.

597
00:54:13,607 --> 00:54:14,881
Very much.

598
00:54:18,727 --> 00:54:21,685
[Soft instrumental music]

599
00:54:51,447 --> 00:54:53,756
<i>KAREN: I had a compass from Denys.</i>

600
00:54:54,367 --> 00:54:56,278
<i>"To steer by,"he said.</i>

601
00:54:57,167 --> 00:54:59,237
<i>But later it came to me...</i>

602
00:54:59,327 --> 00:55:02,160
<i>that we navigated differently.</i>

603
00:55:04,247 --> 00:55:08,160
<i>Perhaps he knew, as I did not...</i>

604
00:55:09,167 --> 00:55:11,397
<i>that the Earth was made round...</i>

605
00:55:11,727 --> 00:55:15,117
<i>so that we would not see
too far down the road.</i>

606
00:55:15,567 --> 00:55:16,841
[Grunts]

607
00:55:45,647 --> 00:55:47,365
You've got syphilis.

608
00:55:52,967 --> 00:55:54,639
KAREN: That's not possible.

609
00:55:56,807 --> 00:55:58,684
Your husband is not ill?

610
00:56:03,167 --> 00:56:04,156
No.

611
00:56:05,487 --> 00:56:07,443
Not the last time I saw him.

612
00:56:08,687 --> 00:56:10,678
That was three months ago.

613
00:56:14,127 --> 00:56:17,278
He's on the border with Delamere.
He would have come home.

614
00:56:17,447 --> 00:56:19,005
These cases vary.

615
00:56:20,367 --> 00:56:22,278
He may have just a touch.

616
00:56:24,087 --> 00:56:25,805
But you are very ill.

617
00:56:34,567 --> 00:56:36,558
Is he the only possibility?

618
00:56:39,487 --> 00:56:40,522
Yes.

619
00:56:41,287 --> 00:56:44,279
DOCTOR: You'll have to go home
to deal with it, you know?

620
00:56:44,367 --> 00:56:48,485
The treatment's difficult,
but they have a thing called Salvarsan.

621
00:56:49,207 --> 00:56:50,356
Arsenic.

622
00:56:53,247 --> 00:56:58,241
And if I'm not cured
then I will be insane, won't I?

623
00:56:58,927 --> 00:57:00,645
You ought to go soon.

624
00:57:02,447 --> 00:57:04,597
I'll have to see your husband.

625
00:57:08,607 --> 00:57:10,086
I will send for him.

626
00:57:10,167 --> 00:57:13,477
These ought to help with the fever
till you get home.

627
00:57:21,687 --> 00:57:25,441
- And what are my chances?
- About even, I'm afraid.

628
00:57:32,087 --> 00:57:33,440
[Exclaims in disbelief]

629
00:57:36,247 --> 00:57:39,045
It's not what I thought
would happen to me now.

630
00:57:54,647 --> 00:57:57,036
FARAH: Muthaiga?
KAREN: What?

631
00:57:57,447 --> 00:57:58,880
FARAH: Your letters.

632
00:58:07,887 --> 00:58:08,876
Excuse me.

633
00:58:11,367 --> 00:58:15,201
I heard you had made it.
I'd have paid anything to see their faces.

634
00:58:15,687 --> 00:58:17,484
Hello.

635
00:58:18,407 --> 00:58:19,681
Would you join us for a drink?

636
00:58:19,767 --> 00:58:22,281
I can't. How is it that you are home?

637
00:58:22,527 --> 00:58:24,404
DENYS: I brought Berkeley back.

638
00:58:24,927 --> 00:58:26,838
- Has he been wounded?
- No, fever.

639
00:58:27,207 --> 00:58:31,166
More than usual, but he'll be all right
as long as the gin holds out.

640
00:58:31,407 --> 00:58:34,479
And you? How is it with the fighting?

641
00:58:36,047 --> 00:58:39,722
We're taking a beating.
It's likely to last for a while.

642
00:58:42,967 --> 00:58:46,118
- I still have your compass.
- Why don't you keep it?

643
00:58:47,567 --> 00:58:49,125
You've earned it.

644
00:58:49,927 --> 00:58:53,476
Besides, I don't always want to know
where I'm going anyway.

645
00:58:58,647 --> 00:59:00,763
KAREN: Please don't let me keep you.

646
00:59:04,207 --> 00:59:06,084
- Are you all right?
- Yes.

647
00:59:07,087 --> 00:59:08,566
Take good care.

648
00:59:10,327 --> 00:59:12,443
- We're behind a story or two.
- Yes.

649
00:59:12,527 --> 00:59:14,916
- When I get back.
- Back? From where?

650
00:59:15,647 --> 00:59:17,683
When you get back, I meant.

651
00:59:19,927 --> 00:59:22,395
BROR: I thought it was malaria.
KAREN: It wasn't.

652
00:59:25,247 --> 00:59:28,319
And you may be all right,
but you have to be seen.

653
00:59:30,207 --> 00:59:34,166
And the others, whoever they are,
I hope they've got it.

654
00:59:35,447 --> 00:59:38,962
It's my fault, no one else's.

655
00:59:42,087 --> 00:59:43,645
[Clock ticking]

656
00:59:44,047 --> 00:59:45,844
I want to go with you.

657
00:59:46,447 --> 00:59:50,725
Someone has to stay here and run things,
and the factory must be finished.

658
00:59:53,047 --> 00:59:55,641
- Can you do that?
- That's little enough.

659
01:00:10,087 --> 01:00:11,361
BROR: I'm sorry.

660
01:00:18,447 --> 01:00:19,516
I'm sorry.

661
01:00:27,647 --> 01:00:29,160
<i>Where's memsahib?</i>

662
01:00:29,767 --> 01:00:31,678
She can come soon enough.

663
01:00:40,247 --> 01:00:43,284
<i>KAREN: Later that day, I left for Mombasa...</i>

664
01:00:43,927 --> 01:00:46,725
<i>and the voyage home to Denmark.</i>

665
01:00:48,607 --> 01:00:50,916
<i>It was a longer journey this time.</i>

666
01:00:52,207 --> 01:00:54,277
<i>The war went on.</i>

667
01:00:54,807 --> 01:00:56,923
<i>I fought my own war.</i>

668
01:00:58,007 --> 01:01:02,364
<i>Arsenic was my ally
against an enemy I never saw.</i>

669
01:01:02,927 --> 01:01:05,316
[African tribal song]

670
01:01:06,127 --> 01:01:09,199
<i>KAREN: I stayed in the room
where I was born...</i>

671
01:01:09,607 --> 01:01:11,325
<i>in Rungstedlund...</i>

672
01:01:11,407 --> 01:01:14,604
<i>and tried to remember the colours of Africa.</i>

673
01:01:26,727 --> 01:01:28,843
<i>There was only the medicine...</i>

674
01:01:29,487 --> 01:01:33,765
<i>and walks with my mother
along a deserted stretch of beach...</i>

675
01:01:34,447 --> 01:01:37,883
<i>and this room in my mother's house.</i>

676
01:01:40,687 --> 01:01:43,724
<i>Denmark had become a stranger to me...</i>

677
01:01:44,287 --> 01:01:45,720
<i>and I to her.</i>

678
01:01:46,967 --> 01:01:49,686
<i>But my mother's house,
I came to know again.</i>

679
01:01:51,127 --> 01:01:55,837
<i>And knew I would come back to it,
sick or well...</i>

680
01:01:56,727 --> 01:01:59,036
<i>sane or mad, someday.</i>

681
01:02:00,287 --> 01:02:02,084
<i>And so I did...</i>

682
01:02:02,847 --> 01:02:04,200
<i>after Tsavo.</i>

683
01:02:24,047 --> 01:02:25,878
[Exclaiming joyfully]

684
01:02:54,607 --> 01:02:56,802
BROR: Almost everyone's got them now.

685
01:03:08,047 --> 01:03:09,719
[Car horn honking]

686
01:03:15,607 --> 01:03:17,438
[Car horn honking]

687
01:03:19,847 --> 01:03:22,236
[Natives talking excitedly]

688
01:03:39,847 --> 01:03:41,565
[Speaking African language]

689
01:03:47,327 --> 01:03:49,079
[Karen exclaiming contentedly]

690
01:04:07,367 --> 01:04:10,837
- I am cooking now.
- I have heard about this.

691
01:04:22,487 --> 01:04:23,886
Are you well?

692
01:04:25,567 --> 01:04:27,523
I am well enough.

693
01:04:28,367 --> 01:04:30,119
Then I am well enough also.

694
01:04:33,047 --> 01:04:34,366
KAREN: What will you do?

695
01:04:34,447 --> 01:04:37,678
I have been thinking I'll hunt.
Safari sort of thing.

696
01:04:38,127 --> 01:04:41,517
They say it'll be quite a business
once the war is over.

697
01:04:42,407 --> 01:04:44,398
KAREN: You wouldn't want to teach?

698
01:04:45,247 --> 01:04:48,045
I would like these Kikuyu to have a school.

699
01:04:49,407 --> 01:04:51,716
There will be a fight about that.

700
01:04:53,247 --> 01:04:54,441
Tanne.

701
01:04:58,287 --> 01:05:00,596
Are you all well?

702
01:05:01,007 --> 01:05:02,725
They say I'm cured.

703
01:05:05,407 --> 01:05:07,204
I won't have children.

704
01:05:15,487 --> 01:05:17,443
Have you thought about us?

705
01:05:21,007 --> 01:05:21,996
Of course.

706
01:05:32,527 --> 01:05:36,281
Belknap says the coffee
will flower after the next rains.

707
01:05:37,687 --> 01:05:41,885
<i>If it does, you'll have to
start thinking about hiring for the harvest...</i>

708
01:05:41,967 --> 01:05:44,561
and how you'll get to market.

709
01:05:45,607 --> 01:05:48,440
[Marching band playing lively tune]

710
01:06:38,647 --> 01:06:41,480
[Marching band continues playing]

711
01:06:55,087 --> 01:06:57,806
- Where would Berkeley be?
- He must be here.

712
01:07:08,887 --> 01:07:10,559
BROR: Who won the match?

713
01:07:18,887 --> 01:07:20,923
Have you got a story for me?

714
01:07:22,487 --> 01:07:23,886
Finch Hatton.

715
01:07:25,247 --> 01:07:27,920
I've been demoted. I was Denys last time.

716
01:07:28,087 --> 01:07:30,442
Would you care for some champagne?

717
01:07:32,407 --> 01:07:35,763
- They said you went home for a while.
- Yes.

718
01:07:36,607 --> 01:07:39,246
- Where's Berkeley?
- It's good to see you.

719
01:07:43,527 --> 01:07:47,236
He's still down with fever. He'll be all right.
Who are all these people?

720
01:07:48,887 --> 01:07:51,196
KAREN: Bror says we'll be a colony soon.

721
01:07:52,807 --> 01:07:54,718
They want it settled now.

722
01:07:55,327 --> 01:07:58,842
<i>They've got a lottery.
"Buy a ticket, win a farm in Africa."</i>

723
01:07:58,927 --> 01:08:01,999
Did you really think
it would stay the way it was?

724
01:08:03,687 --> 01:08:05,359
I thought it might.

725
01:08:07,727 --> 01:08:10,287
- Where is Kanuthia?
- He's dead.

726
01:08:14,127 --> 01:08:16,038
Hello, Denys.

727
01:08:17,247 --> 01:08:20,045
How are you?
Would you join us for a drink?

728
01:08:22,087 --> 01:08:25,921
- It's time to find a pillow.
- Another night then?

729
01:08:30,767 --> 01:08:32,564
Have a good Christmas.

730
01:08:33,767 --> 01:08:35,166
Christmas?

731
01:08:36,367 --> 01:08:37,595
So it is.

732
01:08:40,527 --> 01:08:42,677
[Soft instrumental music]

733
01:09:00,527 --> 01:09:02,961
[Chief speaking African language]

734
01:09:07,727 --> 01:09:10,605
This Chief says children higher than this...

735
01:09:10,807 --> 01:09:12,763
must not learn to read.

736
01:09:14,727 --> 01:09:17,287
Tell him that all the children
must go to school.

737
01:09:17,367 --> 01:09:21,519
No, this is a Chief. You are not a Chief.

738
01:09:21,847 --> 01:09:23,041
KAREN: That's absurd.

739
01:09:23,127 --> 01:09:26,676
It is not good for tall people
to know more than this Chief.

740
01:09:26,807 --> 01:09:30,925
When these children are tall,
then this Chief can be dead.

741
01:09:32,407 --> 01:09:35,365
[Soft instrumental music continues]

742
01:09:48,047 --> 01:09:51,164
[Cheerful instrumental music playing]

743
01:10:05,327 --> 01:10:08,922
Bror, yes. But Denys hired out to tourists,
I can't imagine.

744
01:10:09,007 --> 01:10:11,282
COLE: He's got no other trade
and we've got no choice.

745
01:10:11,367 --> 01:10:13,278
The government's put a stop to the ivory.

746
01:10:13,367 --> 01:10:16,723
KAREN: What will you do then?
COLE: I'll concentrate on the farm.

747
01:10:16,807 --> 01:10:18,320
FELICITY: Hello, the house!

748
01:10:18,407 --> 01:10:19,920
KAREN: Felicity!

749
01:10:20,087 --> 01:10:21,315
How is it you're home?

750
01:10:21,407 --> 01:10:25,685
I'm out. Look. I didn't learn a thing,
but I'm wonderfully clean.

751
01:10:27,767 --> 01:10:30,486
I'll come and see you.
You save me a dance, Berkeley.

752
01:10:36,047 --> 01:10:38,402
[Pleasant instrumental music playing]

753
01:10:38,647 --> 01:10:41,081
What's this nonsense I hear about a school?

754
01:10:41,167 --> 01:10:42,919
I've taken on a young missionary.

755
01:10:43,167 --> 01:10:46,443
He's promised me to do the alphabet first,
and save God for later.

756
01:10:46,527 --> 01:10:48,836
Wogs can't even count their goats.

757
01:10:49,167 --> 01:10:51,237
It's none of your bloody business anyway!

758
01:10:51,327 --> 01:10:53,079
Who the devil are you?

759
01:10:54,967 --> 01:10:57,083
[People shouting]

760
01:10:58,567 --> 01:11:00,797
I wonder if you'd dance with me?

761
01:11:02,567 --> 01:11:04,956
DELAMERE: I think you are
about to apologise.

762
01:11:08,447 --> 01:11:10,199
You do stir things up.

763
01:11:14,167 --> 01:11:17,159
When they said they'd like to read,
how did they put that exactly?

764
01:11:17,247 --> 01:11:18,965
Do they know they'd like Dickens?

765
01:11:19,047 --> 01:11:22,756
- You don't think they should learn to read?
- I think you might have asked them.

766
01:11:22,847 --> 01:11:25,122
KAREN: Did you ask to learn
when you were a child?

767
01:11:25,207 --> 01:11:27,402
KAREN: How can stories
possibly harm them?

768
01:11:27,487 --> 01:11:29,876
They have their own stories,
just not in writing.

769
01:11:30,007 --> 01:11:32,441
Why would you rather keep them ignorant?

770
01:11:32,527 --> 01:11:34,245
They're not ignorant.

771
01:11:34,447 --> 01:11:37,803
I just don't think they should
be turned into little Englishmen.

772
01:11:43,327 --> 01:11:45,045
You do like to change things, don't you?

773
01:11:45,127 --> 01:11:47,243
KAREN: For the better, I hope.

774
01:11:47,887 --> 01:11:50,196
I want my Kikuyu to learn to read.

775
01:11:51,087 --> 01:11:54,443
My Kikuyu. My Limoges. My farm.

776
01:11:54,527 --> 01:11:57,963
- It's an awful lot to own, isn't it?
- I've paid a price for all I own.

777
01:11:58,047 --> 01:12:00,277
What is it exactly that's yours?

778
01:12:01,767 --> 01:12:04,839
We're not owners here,
we're just passing through.

779
01:12:06,687 --> 01:12:09,201
Is life really so damn simple for you?

780
01:12:10,527 --> 01:12:12,995
Perhaps I ask less of it than you do.

781
01:12:13,807 --> 01:12:15,399
I don't believe that at all.

782
01:12:15,487 --> 01:12:17,045
ALL: Happy New Year!

783
01:12:20,567 --> 01:12:23,286
[Traditional New Year song playing]

784
01:12:26,087 --> 01:12:28,078
[All singing]

785
01:13:02,807 --> 01:13:04,035
[Shotgun fires]

786
01:13:07,927 --> 01:13:10,885
[All singing British anthem]

787
01:13:33,447 --> 01:13:37,440
- Happy New Year.
- And for you, too.

788
01:13:56,527 --> 01:13:59,405
Someone has left
her underclothes in the back.

789
01:14:06,327 --> 01:14:08,716
I want you to take a place in town.

790
01:14:14,727 --> 01:14:16,126
Are you sure?

791
01:14:25,007 --> 01:14:27,475
[Melancholic instrumental music]

792
01:14:38,047 --> 01:14:39,036
CHILDREN: Eats.

793
01:14:39,167 --> 01:14:40,202
Eats.

794
01:14:40,287 --> 01:14:41,515
CHILDREN: Eats.

795
01:14:44,567 --> 01:14:46,398
MISSIONARY: He eats.

796
01:14:46,687 --> 01:14:47,676
<i>Elephant.</i>

797
01:14:49,487 --> 01:14:51,682
[Melancholic instrumental music continues]

798
01:15:14,647 --> 01:15:16,046
Give me work.

799
01:15:57,287 --> 01:15:59,926
We've got peace, where is the prosperity?

800
01:16:00,287 --> 01:16:03,677
Why should the prices fall now
just because they're not killing anybody?

801
01:16:04,407 --> 01:16:06,238
Tea's down just as bad.

802
01:16:06,647 --> 01:16:08,797
[Bror shouting in African language]

803
01:16:09,407 --> 01:16:11,682
Do they always have to whip them so?

